Description

This lab contains a path traversal vulnerability in the product image functionality. Although the application blocks common traversal sequences (such as ../), it incorrectly treats user input as a relative path to a default working directory, allowing absolute paths to be used.

Objective

Retrieve the contents of the /etc/passwd file.

Steps to Solve
Intercept the request using Burp Suite while loading a product image.
Identify the parameter used to specify the image file (e.g., filename).

Modify the filename parameter to use an absolute path:

/etc/passwd
Send the modified request to the server.
Observe that the response contains the contents of the /etc/passwd file.
Conclusion

The application attempts to block traversal sequences but fails to prevent access via absolute paths. This results in unauthorized access to sensitive files on the server.
